
  2. Complex Streaming Logic (SyncwebReadSeeker.Read)
  The implementation of on-demand file streaming directly from the cluster (in internal/syncweb/syncweb.go) involves highly complex manual calculations for offsets and
  blocks. While it includes overflow checks, the logic for handling "partial block needs" at the very beginning or end of a read is a high-risk area for off-by-one errors and makes the code difficult to maintain or debug.

  3. Basic Peer Scoring (Measurements.Score)
  The logic used to score and select peers for file transfers (in internal/syncweb/syncweb.go) is quite rudimentary. It only accounts for latency (average time) and error
  rates, completely ignoring bandwidth or concurrency capabilities. In heterogeneous networks, this could lead to sub-optimal peer selection and poor performance.

  5. Performance: Linear Scans for Files
  The API endpoints handling directory listing and finding files (handleSyncwebLs and handleSyncwebFind / collectFolderEntries in internal/commands/serve_syncweb.go) perform
  linear scans over global file lists. This lack of indexed search means these operations will become a severe performance bottleneck and scale poorly as the number of files
  grows into the hundreds of thousands or millions.

  6. Reinvented Cache Logic (eventsCache)
  In GetEvents, the invalidation logic for the event buffer uses manual sequencing (eventsSeq) to implement a cache. This custom implementation is robust but adds unnecessary complexity; it could likely be simplified or replaced entirely with a more standard, less error-prone caching pattern or library.
